fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2mitche:   ^*bBidding After Opener's Reverse^*N
We are going to start with a discussion of reverses and bidding after Opener reverses. 
First, we need to make sure that we agree on what a reverse is.

A reverse is a non-jump rebid by opener, in a higher ranking suit than his first bid suit, and below 2 of responder's suit.
When the bid is made after a 1 over 1 response, the reverse shows extra values. 
Examples of reverse auctions: 
1@c – 1@s/ 2@d     or     1@h – 1NT/2@s. 
Opener's first suit is always longer than the second bid suit - at least 5-4 in shape (*)|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at| 
But note: 1@c – 1@h / 2@s is not a reverse, it is a ^*b"jump-shift"^*n and is forcing to game 
- because 2@s is ^*uabove^*n 2@h, responder's suit.
 
(*Expert note:  Sometimes you may reverse to establish a force and describe your hand pattern. 
Example: @sKQx, @hx, @dAKJ, @cAK10xxx  
After 1@C – 1@S by responder, it would be foolish to stop short of game. So opener bids 2@d (forcing, 1 round), 
and over any rebid by responder, raises to 3@S. 
Responder will know opener has 3 good spades and a singleton heart and bid game on a hand like 
@sJ10xxx  @hKxxx  @dxx  @cxx  
With decent spades and working cards in the minors, (ex: @sAJxxx, @hxxxx, @dxx, @cQx) 
an expert pair might even reach 6@s)|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|

A reverse is forcing for 1 round.
Some players like to say they are game-forcing, but I think they are best played as forcing for 1 round, 
showing 5 or 6 losers (16+ points with good suits).  
Example hand for a reverse: 
@s 7 @h KQJ6 @d AQJ83, @c K54.  You open 1@d, and over 1@s, you bid 2@h to show a 6-loser hand 
with 4 hearts and more diamonds.
|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
Responder may have kept the bidding open on a very poor hand (with 10 losers)..... so you need to have a way 
for responder to distinguish between  - a hopeless hand <=> one that will offer a chance for game or slam.

When responder has a very poor hand, he may use a ^*u2NT^*n (A!) call to slow  down the auction here. 
Example: responder holds
@sQxxx, @hxx, @dxxx, @cQJxx. 
If the auction had been 1@d – 1@s / 2@h, responder's hand is about as poor as it could be  ... but he must bid. 

^*U2NT by responder forces opener to rebid 3@C^*n,   and then responder will bid 3@D to end the auction.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

Most pairs also play that responder's rebid of 2 of his opening suit shows: 
a 5+ card suit and a weak hand, without good support for either of opener's suits. 

Responder's bids after the 2NT - 3@c relay:

a) Pass opener's 3@C rebid with 6+ clubs and no support for either of opener's suits, 
e.g. @sQxxx, @hxx, @dx, @cQJ10xxx.  
If opener's first suit was clubs, then passing 3@c relay shows 3 card support.|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


at| 

b) Bid one of opener's suits with 3+ card support. This is an absolute signoff. 
Opener's 3@C promises a minimum reverse, and responder denies the strength to bid game. 
Example: @sKxxx, @hJxx, @dx, @cJxxxx. 
Relay to 2NT and then bid 3@h. If you're lucky, you will survive.|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


at|

Notice that I left out a rebid of responder's ^*uown^*n suit after the 2NT relay. Some pairs play that as a strong 
response, showing (usually), a 6+ card suit and at least game-going values.
Example:   
@sKQTxxx   @hxx   @dKx   @cAxx 
Bid 2NT, and after the 3@C forced response, bid 3@s. 
Opener cannot pass, and if he has a hand like @sJx, @hAKxx, @dAQxxx, @cKx, you will soar into 6@S. 
|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
If opener has a hand strong enough to bid to game opposite a 5-6 point dummy, he will bid something other 
than 3@c. Example: 
@sJ, @HAKJ10, @DAKQxx, @cK10x will make game opposite as little as @sJxxx, @hQx. @d10xx, @cQJxx. 

Opener's rebids are as follows (when breaking the "puppet 3@c" = GF): 

a) With extra length in his first bid suit and 4-5 losers, opener rebids his first suit. 
Example @sKx, @hKQJx, @dAKxxxx, @cx rebids 3@d. 
NOTE: this may be based on playing strength, not high cards.|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


at| 

b) With extra length in his second bid suit and 4 losers, opener rebids his second suit. 
Example: @sx, @hKQJxx, @dAKJ10xx, 
Note, since diamonds must be longer than hearts, this auction promises 5-6 or longer in hearts and diamonds.|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|

c) With a 3-card support for responder's suit, opener may rebid 3 of responder' suit. 
Example: @sQJ8, @hAK93, @dAK1084, @c3|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


at|  

d) With a stopper in the unbid suit and 4-5 losers, opener may bid 3NT.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


at| 

Of course, responder may have a better hand. Supporting either of opener's suits shows 8+ support points 
and is game forcing. Example: AQxxx, Jxxx, x, xxx 
1@d-1@s / 2@h-3@h

I like to treat the 4th suit by responder as showing a partial stopper and about 8-10 points, something 
like KQxx, xxx, Jx, Q10xx. The reason is that opener will be able to evaluate a holding like Jxx as 
enough to risk 3NT.  
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
OK – quiz 
The auction has gone 1@D – 1@s/ 2@H
What is your action on these hands
1:  @sAJxx, @h10xx, @dKxxx, @cxx   |
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


at|

Answer:  3@d – all of your high cards are working and game is likely. |
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|

2: @sKQxxx, @hxx, @dxx, @cJxxx  |
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


at|

Answer:  Rebid 2@S. This is a weak bid. |
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|

3: @sKQxxx, @hx, @dJxx, @cQJxx  |
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|

Answer:  Rebid 2NT. 
- Partner will relay to 3@C and you will rebid 3NT 
– If partner rebids 3@d or 3@h over 2NT, you will bid 5@d 
- Of course, if partner rebids 3@s, you will happily bid 4@s, since opener will not have 3 small spades 
(most of the time). |
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


at|

4: @sQJxxx, @hQxxx, @dKx, @cxx  |
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|

Answer:  Just bid a quiet 3@h.. opener will know whether to settle for game or look for slam. 
No need to jump to game here.

